) planes of CuO (JCPDS No.48-1548). After coating with GQDs, the Co3O4@CuO@GQDs exhibits similar diffraction peaks arising from Co3O4@CuO, indicating a well-kept microstructure. In addition, we can also observe a broad peak at the range of 20°–25° because of the incorporation of GQDs. TGA measurement was carried out in air atmosphere to track the thermal behavior of Co-Cu-BTC. As indicated in Fig. 1b, the first mass loss between 100 ∼ 300 °C can be explained by the evaporation of solvents (methanol) trapped in pores of Co-Cu-BTC and the partial oxidation of organic ligands. The following weight loss between 300 and 400 °C can be ascribed to the degradation of the organic ligand and generation of Co3O4 and CuO. Note that no more weight loss is detected at an elevated temperature above 400 °C, indicating the complete oxidation of Co-Cu-BTC.
